<emphasis bold="true" box="[253,421,1612,1634]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="453">Chalepus bicolor</emphasis>
(Olivier, 1792)
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="0.[173,659,1655,1729]" lastBlockId="0.[707,1194,771,1296]" pageId="0" pageNumber="453">
My previous account of this species did not mention the egg because it was absent from the mine from which I reared an adult. This was possibly a secondary mine, made by a larva that had wandered from its original leaf. The two other mines I examined had an egg attached to the lower surface near the tip of the leaf (
<figureCitation box="[893,950,850,871]" captionStart="Figs" captionStartId="1.[175,215,1569,1588]" captionTargetBox="[151,1171,210,1546]" captionTargetId="figure-0@1.[151,1171,194,1546]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="Figs. 1â€“8. 1) Egg of Chalepus bicolor, lateral view); 2) Egg of Chalepus walshii, dorsal view; 3) Larva and leaf mine of Microrhopala xerene; 4) Abandoned mine of M. xerene, with pupal blister torn open; 5) Mine of Sumitrosis inaequalis in Symphyotrichum cordifolium; 6) Mine of Dibolia chelones, showing two frass types; 7) Mature larva of D. chelones; 8) Five young larvae of D. chelones in a single leaf." pageId="0" pageNumber="453">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). The egg is oval, about 
<quantity box="[707,780,877,898]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
by 
<quantity box="[817,893,877,898]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.0" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" unit="mm" value="0.9">0.9 mm</quantity>
, and covered with a transparent secretion that glues it to the lower leaf surface. This in turn is capped by a hollow, rounded structure that is covered with minute bumps. This structure is broken into two or more pieces once the egg is hatched (and I have not observed unhatched eggs), but it is a secreted covering for the egg rather than a broken eggshell. The larva mines directly into the leaf without damaging the exposed surface of the egg, so it is unclear how the covering comes to be hollow and broken.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="453" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="0.[707,1194,771,1296]" pageId="0" pageNumber="453">
Adults feed on the upper surface of leaves of 
<taxonomicName box="[707,1004,1195,1217]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Poaceae" genus="Dichanthelium" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="clandestinum">
<emphasis box="[707,1004,1195,1217]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="453">Dichanthelium clandestinum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) (
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barnhart" authorityYear="1895" baseAuthorityName="R.Br." box="[1070,1156,1196,1217]" class="Liliopsida" family="Poaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Poales" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Poaceae</taxonomicName>
) in August, producing whitish patches similar to those made by 
<taxonomicName authority="(Crotch)" baseAuthorityName="Crotch" baseAuthorityYear="1873" box="[792,1038,1248,1270]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Chalepus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="walshii">
<emphasis box="[792,954,1248,1270]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="453">Chalepus walshii</emphasis>
(Crotch)
</taxonomicName>
on other grasses (
<bibRefCitation author="Eiseman" box="[713,850,1275,1296]" pageId="0" pageNumber="453" pagination="351 - 359" refId="ref3639" refString="Eiseman, C. S. 2014. New host records and other notes on North American leaf-mining Chrysomelidae (Coleoptera). The Coleopterists Bulletin 68 (3): 351 - 359." type="journal article" year="2014">Eiseman 2014</bibRefCitation>
) but more irregular in outline.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
